<section xml:id="sec-linear_ineq" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Linear Inequalities</title>

  <definition xml:id="def-linear_inequality">
    <title>Linear Inequality</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
	A <term>linear inequality</term>
	<idx>
	  <h>Inequality</h>
	  <h>Linear</h>
	</idx>
	in the variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> is an expression that can be placed in one of the following forms
	<ul>
	  <li><m>ax + by \lt c</m>,</li>
	  <li><m>ax + by \leq c</m>,</li>
	  <li><m>ax + by \gt c</m>, or</li>
	  <li><m>ax + by \geq c</m>.</li>
	</ul>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <definition xml:id="def-solution_inequality">
    <title>Solution to an Inequality</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
	A <term>solution</term>
	<idx>
	  <h>Inequality</h>
	  <h>Linear</h>
	  <h>Solution</h>
	</idx>
	to an inequality in the variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> is an ordered pair <m>(a,b)</m> that make the equation true when
	<ol>
	  <li>
	    the first coordinate, <m>a</m>, is substituted into the inequality for <m>x</m>, and
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    the second coordinate, <m>b</m>, is substituted into the inequality for <m>y</m>.
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <definition xml:id="def-graph_inequality">
    <title>Graph of an Inequality</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
	The <term>graph</term>
	<idx>
	  <h>Inequality</h>
	  <h>Linear</h>
	  <h>Graph</h>
	</idx>
	of an inequality in the variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> consists of all the points in the plane that are solutions to the inequality.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Graph the linear inequality <m>2x + 3y \lt 5</m>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
	The graph of <m>2x + 3y \lt 5</m> consists of all the points that are below the line <m>2x + 3y = 5</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
	We use a dashed line to indicate the points on the line <m>2x + 3y = 5</m> are <alert>not</alert> a solution to the inequality and shade the portion of the plane beneath the line to indicate those points are solutions to the inequality.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-2x_3y_lt_5">
	<caption>The graph of the linear inequality <m>2x + 3y \lt 5</m>.</caption>
	<image xml:id="img-2x_3y_lt_5">
	  <latex-image xml:id="tikz-2x_3y_lt_5">
	    <xi:include parse="text" href="tex/2x_3y_lt_5.tex"/>
	  </latex-image>
	</image>
      </figure>
    </solution>
  </example>


  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Graph the linear inequality <m>2x + 3y \leq 5</m>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
	The graph of <m>2x + 3y \leq 5</m> consists of all the points that are on or below the line <m>2x + 3y = 5</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
	We use a solid line to indicate the points on the line <m>2x + 3y = 5</m> are a solution to the linear inequality and shade the portion of the plane beneath the line to indicate that those points are also solutions.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-2x_3y_leq_5">
	<caption>The graph of the linear inequality <m>2x + 3y \leq 5</m>.</caption>
	<image xml:id="img-2x_3y_leq_5">
	  <latex-image xml:id="tikz-2x_3y_leq_5">
	    <xi:include parse="text" href="tex/2x_3y_leq_5.tex"/>
	  </latex-image>
	</image>
	
      </figure>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Graph the linear inequality <m>2x + 3y \gt -5</m>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
	The graph of <m>2x + 3y \gt -5</m> consists of all the points that are above the line <m>2x + 3y = -5</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
	We use a dashed line to indicate the points on the line <m>2x + 3y = -5</m> are <alert>not</alert> solutions to the inequality and shade the portion of the plane above the line to indicate that those points are solutions.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-2x_3y_gt_-5">
	<caption>The graph of the linear inequality <m>2x + 3y \gt -5</m>.</caption>
	<image xml:id="img-2x_3y_gt_-5">
	  <latex-image xml:id="tikz-2x_3y_gt_-5">
	    <xi:include parse="text" href="tex/2x_3y_gt_-5.tex"/>
	  </latex-image>
	</image>
      </figure>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Graph the linear inequality <m>2x + 3y \geq -5</m>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
	The graph of <m>2x + 3y \lt -5</m> consists of all the points that are either on or above the line <m>2x + 3y = -5</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
	We use a solid line to indicate the points on the line <m>2x + 3y = -5</m> are solutions to the linear inequality and shade the portion of the plane above the line to indicate that those points are also solutions.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-2x_3y_geq_-5">
	<caption>The graph of the linear inequality <m>2x + 3y \geq -5</m>.</caption>

	<image xml:id="img-2x_3y_geq_-5">
	  <latex-image>
	    <xi:include parse="text" href="tex/2x_3y_geq_-5.tex"/>
	  </latex-image>
	</image>
      </figure>
    </solution>
  </example>
  
  <subsection>
    <title>Absolute Value and Inequality</title>

    <definition xml:id="def-linear_absolute_value_inequality">
      <title>Linear Absolute Value Inequality</title>
      <statement>
	<p>
	  A <term>linear absolute value inequality</term>
	  <idx>
	    <h>Inequality</h>
	    <h>Linear</h>
	    <h>Absolute Value</h>
	  </idx>
	  in the variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> is an expression that can be placed in one of the following forms
	  <ul>
	    <li>
	      <m>\abs{ax + by + c} \lt d</m>,
	    </li>
	    <li>
	      <m>\abs{ax + by + c} \leq d</m>,
	    </li>
	    <li>
	      <m>\abs{ax + by + c} \gt d</m>, or
	    </li>
	    <li>
	      <m>\abs{ax + by + c} \geq d</m>.
	    </li>
	  </ul>
	</p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Recall from <xref ref="def-1_distance" />, for any number <m>d</m>,
      <me>\abs{d} = \abs{d - 0}</me>
      measures the distance between <m>d</m> and the origin on the number line.
      We can see from 
      <me>\abs{-d} = \abs{(-d)^2} = \abs{d^2} = \abs{d}</me>
      that <m>d</m> and <m>-d</m> are the same distance from the origin.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-abs_val_two_sol">
      <caption>The distance between <m>d</m> and the origin, and between <m>-d</m> and the origin.</caption>
      <image xml:id="img-abs_val_two_sol">
	<latex-image xml:id="tikz-abs_val_two_sol">
	  <xi:include parse="text" href="tex/abs_val_two_sol.tex"/>
	</latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
      This observation tells us for an linear absolute value inequality of the form <m>\abs{ax + by + c} \lt d</m>, we are looking for the points <m>(x,y)</m> in the plane such that the number <m>ax + by + c</m> is less than <m>d</m> units away from 0 on the number line.
      From <xref ref="fig-abs_val_two_sol"/> we can see these are the solutions to <alert>both</alert>
      <me>-d \lt ax + by + c
      \quad\text{and}\quad
      ax + by + c \lt d.
      </me>
      If we rewrite these as the linear inequalities 
      <me>-d - c \lt ax + by + c
      \quad\text{and}\quad
      ax + by \lt -c + d,
      </me>
      then we can see the solutions to <m>\abs{ax + by + c} \lt d</m> are the points that are above the line <m>-d - c = ax + by + c</m> and below the line <m>ax + by = -c + d</m>.
      Similarly, the solutions to <m>\abs{ax + by + c} \leq d</m> are the points that are either on or between the lines <m>-d - c = ax + by + c</m> and below the line <m>ax + by = -c + d</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      For an linear absolute value inequality of the form <m>\abs{ax + by + c} > d</m>, the observation above tells us we are looking for the points <m>(x,y)</m> in the plane such that the number <m>ax + by + c</m> is more than <m>d</m> units away from 0 on the number line.
      From <xref ref="fig-abs_val_two_sol"/> we can see these are solutions to <alert>either</alert>
      <me>ax + by +c \lt -d
      \quad\text{or}\quad
      d \lt ax + by + c.
      </me>
      If we rewrite these as the liner inequalities
      <me>ax + by \lt -c - d
      \quad\text{or}\quad
      -c + d \lt ax + by,
      </me>
      then we can see the solutions to <m>\abs{ax + by + c} \gt d</m> are the points that are below the line <m>ax + by = -c - d</m> or above the line <m>ax + by = -c + d</m>.
      Similarly, the solutions to the linear absolute value inequality <m>\abs{ax + by + c} \geq d</m> are the points that are either on or below the line <m>ax + by = -c - d</m> or on or above the line <m>ax + by = -c + d</m>.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Graph the linear absolute value inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \lt 5</m>.
	</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
	<p>
	  The solutions to the inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \lt 5</m> are the points that are solutions to <alert>both</alert> of the linear inequalities
	  <me>-5 \lt 2x + 3y \quad\text{and}\quad 2x + 3y \lt 5.</me>
	  This means the graph is the <alert>overlap</alert> between <xref ref="fig-2x_3y_lt_5"/> and <xref ref="fig-2x_3y_gt_-5"/>.
	  That is, the points that are between the lines
	  <me>2x + 3y = -5 \quad\text{and}\quad 2x + 3y = 5.</me>
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="fig-abs_2x_3y_lt_5">
	  <caption>The graph of the linear absolute value inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \lt 5</m>.</caption>
	  <image xml:id="img-abs_2x_3y_lt_5">
	    <latex-image xml:id="tikz-abs_2x_3y_lt_5">
	      <xi:include parse="text" href="tex/abs_2x_3y_lt_5.tex"/>
	    </latex-image>
	  </image>
	</figure>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Graph the linear absolute value inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \leq 5</m>.
	</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
	<p>
	  The solutions to the inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \leq 5</m> are the points that are solutions to <alert>both</alert> of the linear inequalities
	  <me>-5 \leq 2x + 3y \quad\text{and}\quad 2x + 3y \leq 5.</me>
	  This means the graph is the <alert>overlap</alert> between <xref ref="fig-2x_3y_leq_5"/> and <xref ref="fig-2x_3y_geq_-5"/>.
	  That is, the points that are either on or between the lines
	  <me>2x + 3y = -5 \quad\text{and}\quad 2x + 3y = 5.</me>
	</p>
	<figure>
	  <caption>The graph of the linear absolute value inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \leq 5</m>.</caption>

	  <image>
	    <latex-image>
	      <xi:include parse="text" href="tex/abs_2x_3y_leq_5.tex"/>
	    </latex-image>
	  </image>
	</figure>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Graph the linear absolute value inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \gt 5</m>.
	</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
	<p>
	  The solutions to the inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \lt 5</m> are the points that are solutions to <alert>either</alert> 
	  <me>
	    -5 \lt 2x + 3y
	    \quad\text{or}\quad
	    2x + 3y \lt 5.
	  </me>
	  This means the graph is the <alert>combination</alert> of the graphs for the linear inequalities
	  <me>2x + 3 \lt -5
	  \quad\text{and}\quad
	  2x + 3y \gt 5.</me>
	  That is, the points that are either above the line <m>2x + 3y = 5</m> or below the line <m>2x + 3y = -5</m>.
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="fig-abs_2x_3y_gt_5">
	  <caption>The graph of the linear absolute value inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \gt 5</m>.</caption>
	  <image xml:id="img-abs_2x_3y_gt_5">
	    <latex-image xml:id="tikz-abs_2x_3y_gt_5">
	      <xi:include parse="text" href="tex/abs_2x_3y_gt_5.tex"/>
	    </latex-image>
	  </image>
	</figure>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Graph the linear absolute value inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \leq 5</m>.
	</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
	<p>
	  The solutions to the inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \geq 5</m> are the points that are solutions to <alert>either</alert> the linear inequality
	  <m>-5 \leq 2x + 3y</m>
	  or the linear inequality
	  <m>2x + 3y \leq 5.</m>
	  This means the graph is the <alert>combination</alert> of the graphs for the linear inequalities
	  <me>2x + 3 \leq -5
	  \quad\text{and}\quad
	  2x + 3y \geq 5.</me>
	  That is, the points that are either on or above the line <m>2x + 3y = 5</m>, or on or below the line <m>2x + 3y = -5</m>.
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="fig-abs_2x_3y_geq_5">
	  <caption>The graph of the linear absolute value inequality <m>\abs{2x + 3y} \leq 5</m>.</caption>
	  <image xml:id="img-abs_2x_3y_geq_5">
	    <latex-image xml:id="tikz-abs_2x_3y_geq_5">
	      <xi:include parse="text" href="tex/abs_2x_3y_geq_5.tex"/>
	    </latex-image>
	  </image>
	</figure>
      </solution>
    </example>

  </subsection>

